<DOC><DOCNO> AP880819-0033 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 0131EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u p AM-CVN--Reagan 1stLd-Writethru a0702 08-19 0321</FIRST><SECOND>AM-CVN--Reagan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0702,320</SECOND><HEAD>Reagan's Biographer Visits Ranch</HEAD><NOTE>Eds: UPDATES with Reagan phone call to Bush at end of convention,picking up 3rd graf pvs, ``Fitzwater said...White House.''</NOTE><DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   President Reagan telephoned VicePresident George Bush to congratulate him after his acceptancespeech at the Republican National Convention, the president'sspokesman said.   Marlin Fitzwater, assistant to the president for pressrelations, said Reagan told the vice president, ``Congratulations.It was a great speech, and we're all with you, George.''   Fitzwater said the president and First Lady Nancy Reagan watchedthe speech on television at their ranch north of here, where theyare vacationing.   Reagan, who also watched Wednesday night's conventionproceedings on television, met earlier Thursday with theprize-winning author who is writing his biography.   Fitzwater said Reagan was meeting Thursday with Edmund Morris,who won the Pulitzer Prize for biography for his book, ``The Riseof Theodore Roosevelt.'' Morris, who has been given special accessto the president for the project, has declined to talk withreporters about the book, explaining that was part of his agreementwith the White House.   Fitzwater said Reagan did routine paperwork and went horsebackriding with Mrs. Reagan after breakfast.   He signed five bills Wednesday, including one increasing theamount of money for presidential transitions, beginning with hisearly next year. The amount for the incoming president and vicepresident is increased from $2 million to $3.5 million and theamount for the outgoing president and vice president goes from $1million to $1.5 million.   The president goes to Irvine, Calif., next Tuesday for afund-raising luncheon for Sen. Pete Wilson, R-Calif., and willcontinue on to Los Angeles, where he will likely make a jointappearance with Bush on Wednesday.   The Reagans will return to Washington on Sept. 8 and areexpected to visit the ranch once more, at Thanksgiving, before thepresident's term ends in January.</TEXT></DOC>